"   <div id=\"basicsTopicLeft\">",
"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Detached retina (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/detached-retina-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H28271032\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is a detached retina?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;A detached retina is a serious eye condition that causes vision changes. It can lead to vision loss and even blindness.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      The retina is a layer of tissue at the back of the eye (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_picture graphicRef84036 \" href=\"mobipreview.htm?31/13/31953\">",
"       picture 1",
"      </a>",
"      ). It sends nerve signals to the brain about what we see. If the retina gets a tear or hole, it can start to peel off the back of the eye. If this happens, the person can lose the ability to see. &nbsp; &nbsp;",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      A detached retina most often happens for no clear reason. But having diabetes or getting an eye injury can raise the risk of a detached retina.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H28271047\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of a detached retina?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The symptoms include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Seeing dark or floating spots (doctors call these &ldquo;floaters&rdquo;). These can look like:",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"hyphen-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        A spiderweb",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        A large spot that comes and goes - It might look like a big fly.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Many small black spots",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Small floaters are very common. They usually don&rsquo;t mean there is an eye problem. But when they happen suddenly and are very large, they can be a sign of a problem.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Other symptoms can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Seeing flashes of light &ndash; The flashes might be easier to see at night or in a dark room.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Losing vision &ndash; A person might not be able to see detail, or only see shapes.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H28271062\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Should I see a doctor or nurse?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. See your doctor or nurse right away if you suddenly lose vision or see flashes of light, large floaters, or many floaters. These could be warning signs of a detached retina. &nbsp;",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Seeing floaters and flashes of light can also be a sign of a condition called &ldquo;posterior vitreous detachment.&rdquo; This condition is fairly common. It is not as serious as a detached retina. But people who get a posterior vitreous detachment need to see a doctor on a regular basis to make sure it does not become a detached retina. &nbsp;",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H28271076\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there a test for detached retina?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. To check for a detached retina, your doctor can do an eye exam and test your vision.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If the doctor thinks you might have a detached retina, you will need to see an eye doctor. The eye doctor will do a procedure called a &ldquo;dilated eye exam.&rdquo; This means the doctor gives you eye drops that help him or her see inside your eye. Then the doctor looks at your retina to see if it is detached. He or she might use some special devices or lights that help him or her see the retina.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      You might also have a test called an &ldquo;ultrasound&rdquo; done on the eye. This is an imaging test that uses sound waves to create pictures of the inside of the eye. It can show a detached retina.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H28271091\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is a detached retina treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;If the retina is detached, doctors treat it right away. This can help keep it from getting worse and causing blindness. Doctors can treat a detached retina by:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Injecting a bubble of gas into the eye. This can push the retina back into place.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Doing surgery. Doctors use different methods to put the detached retina back and hold it in place.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H28271106\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       More on this topic",
"      </span>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <a class=\"medical medical_basics\" href=\"mobipreview.htm?11/34/11810?source=see_link\">",
